 |publisher= [[PennWell Corporation]]
 |journal = [[Oil & Gas Journal]]
 |issue = 30
 |volume = 102
 |date=2004-08-09
 |accessdate=2012-12-19
 |id = {{subscription required}}}}
</ref>

In 2005, [[Royal Dutch Shell]] announced that [[Shell in situ conversion process|its ''in-situ'' process]] could become competitive for oil prices over $30&nbsp;per barrel ($190/m<sup>3</sup>).<ref name=rockymountainnews>
{{cite news
| publisher= Rocky Mountain News
| last=Seebach | first = Linda
| url= http://www.rockymountainnews.com/drmn/news_columnists/article/0,1299,DRMN_86_4051709,00.html 
| title =Shell's ingenious approach to oil shale is pretty slick
| date = 2005-09-02
| accessdate=2007-06-02
| archiveurl = http://web.archive.org/web/20080420145917/http://www.rockymountainnews.com/drmn/news_columnists/article/0,1299,DRMN_86_4051709,00.html
| archivedate = 2008-04-20}}
</ref>  A 2004 report by the [[United States Department of Energy]] stated that both the Shell technology and technology used in the [[Stuart Oil Shale Project]] could be competitive at prices above $25 per barrel, and that the [[Viru Keemia Grupp]] expected full-scale production to be economical at prices above $18&nbsp;per barrel ($130/m<sup>3</sup>).<ref name=fossilenergy/><ref name=schmidt>
{{Cite journal
| last = Schmidt | first = S. J.
| title = New directions for shale oil:path to a secure new oil supply well into this century: on the example of Australia
| journal = [[Oil Shale (journal)|Oil Shale. A Scientific-Technical Journal]]
| publisher = Estonian Academy Publishers
| volume =20
| issue =3
| pages =333<U+2013>346
| year = 2003
